metadata.name: Inner Perception #4
metadata.description:
Each generated artwork of this collection showcases a different perspective on a single scene. The collection highlights the diversity and subjectivity of human perception, revealing how our individual experiences, perspectives, and interpretations shape the way we see the world. "Inner Perception" invites viewers to reflect on their own perspectives and promotes a deeper understanding of the impact that personal interpretation has on shaping our perceptions of reality.

Use buttons ("2" - 4000px, "3" - 8000px, "4" - 12000px, "5" - 16000px) to change canvas size and "s" to download image as PNG

Created with p5.js

metadata.name: cosmic circles #39
metadata.description:
'cosmic circles' is a geometric representation of cosmic phenomena.

Iterations undergoing an eclipse contain a larger circle casting its shadow upon the grid. The grid itself contains planets orbiting suns, dwarf planets, stars or sun rays.

5% chance of sun rays, 50% chance of an eclipse.
6 colour palettes.


100% code (p5.js)

metadata.name: BRIDGE #403
metadata.description:
BRIDGE is a collaborative project for fx(hash), conceived by Camille Roux. The project was announced on Twitter on Feb. 7, 2022 [1]. Artists were given two weeks to contribute code that would draw tiles representing a bridge, in their own style. Artists were free to implement their own artistic vision, subject to one simple constraint: Respect the coordinates of the tiles for each iteration of the art. 

Each iteration has a default style determined randomly at mint. This style is named in the features and displayed in the thumbnail. However, each iteration includes all styles, and you can cycle through them by clicking on or touching the image. Styles will be shown in the order in which they are listed under INCLUDED STYLES.

Press "s" to save a screenshot.

THE STORY

I'm Camille Roux. I planned to do a lot of collab this year with fx(hash) artists I like, but it takes too much time, or maybe I like too many artists :) Some days ago, I woke up with this idea in mind: "Hey! What if I make a collaboration with all the artists I like at once!" This is how the BRIDGE project was born.

Moreover, I love the mutual aid and solidarity between fx(hash) generative artists. The BRIDGE can be seen as a symbol of the link between us ♥️.

The project has also served as an inspiration for participants to extend and develop their coding skills outside their usual areas of interest. The code for the entire project remains available on GitHub [2].

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #130
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive — Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees’ Schotter (1968)— a classic piece of generative art history — as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver’d on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there’s a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares — since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‘dithering’ can be larger than a single ‘pixel’ size — when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND

metadata.name: fields, wireframes #100
metadata.description:
The second part of our generative sketchbook of ideas for a sculpture garden.

Fields builds off Stan Allen's seminal essay "Field Conditions" in which he laid out a prototypical theory of architectural field schemes. Field Conditions are opposed to figural or object-based compositional strategies and approach a site from a systemic point of view. These fields contain a range of possible wall-types. Some produce enclosures, while others dictate a wandering path.

Built with p5.js
By office ca
2022

metadata.name: Mind Spa #30
metadata.description:
You breathe, focus, drift off, let go, and you do it all over again. From blurry to solid, scattered to connected, chasing around to sitting behind. Not to change the way it flows, but to be with your mind as it goes.

It’s the state of mind during meditation. I hope you could gain a bit of inner peace enjoying this one.
